tickets.description:
During the insert \(using
DatabaseOperation.CLEAN\_INSERT\) of data stored in an
xml file, only columns with real values \(I mean not
null\) on the first line will be inserted.

Here's an example \(on oracle 8.1.7\) :

test@TEST&amp;gt; create table test\_table \(ID INT PRIMARY KEY,
NAME VARCHAR2\(100\)\);

first try with this xml file : 
&amp;lt;dataset&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;TEST\_TABLE ID='1'/&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;TEST\_TABLE ID='2' NAME='Joe'/&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;TEST\_TABLE ID='3' NAME='Bill'/&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;/dataset&amp;gt;

test@TEST&amp;gt; select \* from test\_table;

ID NAME
\-- ----
1 NULL
2 NULL
3 NULL

second try with this :
&amp;lt;dataset&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;TEST\_TABLE ID='2' NAME='Joe'/&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;TEST\_TABLE ID='1'/&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;TEST\_TABLE ID='3' NAME='Bill'/&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;/dataset&amp;gt;

test@TEST&amp;gt; select \* from test\_table;

ID NAME
\-- ----
2 Joe 
1 NULL
3 Bill

I suppose the metadata for the insert sql order is
based on the first xml line.

when calling setObject \(in SimplePreparedStatement - it 
isn't relevant for PreparedBatchStatement because the 
BEA driver doesn't support it\), if a null is passed as the 
value, the driver throws a null pointer exception. The 
driver expects you to call setNull if you want to pass a 
null. This hack fixed my problem:

public void addValue\(Object value, DataType 
dataType\)
throws TypeCastException, SQLException
\{
Object typeCastValue = dataType.typeCast\(value\);
if \(typeCastValue \!= null\) \{
\_statement.setObject\(++\_index, typeCastValue, 
dataType.getSqlType\(\)\);
\} else \{
\_statement.setNull\(++\_index, 
dataType.getSqlType\(\)\);
\}
\}

