tickets.description:
We have a problem with using DbUnit on Sybase ASE. An
prepared insert statement throws an SQLException if
executed with executeUpdate\(\) on a table with an insert
trigger as it returns not only an update count. So I
had to turn off batch statements and modify the calls
to executeUpdate\(\) into two separate calls to execute\(\)
and getUpdateCount\(\):

boolean r = \_statement.execute\(sql\);
if\(\!r\)
\{
result += \_statement.getUpdateCount\(\);
\}

We have a problem with numeric values written to the
database with the jConnect 5.5 driver for Sybase ASE
12.x. Setting the parameter of a prepared statement
with setObject\( int column, Object value, int type\)
implicitly sets the scale to 0. So all numeric values
are truncated. I did a workaround, setting the scale
explicitly for all numeric values.
Here an example of this workaround:

public void addValue\(Object value, DataType dataType\)
throws TypeCastException, 
SQLException
\{
Object v = dataType.typeCast\(value\);
int t = dataType.getSqlType\(\);
\_index += 1;

if\(\(t == Types.NUMERIC\) &amp;amp;&amp;amp; v instanceof BigDecimal\)
\{
\_statement.setObject\(\_index, v, t,
\(\(BigDecimal\)v\).scale\(\)\);
\}
else
\{
\_statement.setObject\(\_index, v, t\);
\}
\}

But perhaps the data type itself should now something
about the scale of its value.

