tickets.description:
If \_statement.close\(\) succeeds, it must be assumed 
that \_resultSet.close\(\) has already occurred \(see 
Statement.close javadocs -- URL below\).

The OpenBase JDBC adaptor throws a 
NullPointerException if this situation occurs, which is not 
trapped and thus kills DBUnit.

Code from AbstractResultSetTable.java:

protected ResultSet \_resultSet;
\[...\]
public void close\(\) throws DataSetException
\{
try
\{
if \(\_statement \!= null\)
\{
\_statement.close\(\);
\_statement = null;
\}


if \(\_resultSet \!= null\)
\{
\_resultSet.close\(\);
\_resultSet = null;
\}
\}

catch \(SQLException e\)
\{
throw new DataSetException\(e\);
\}
\}


From 
http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.4.2/docs/api/java/sql/Statem
ent.html\#close\(\)

\[...\]When a Statement object is closed, its current 
ResultSet object, if one exists, is also closed.

In dbunit 1.5 it was possible to create a ResultSetTable 
directly from a ResultSet. In 2.0, you have to seperately 
define the metadata, even though a result set 
essentially has that in it already. The requisit method 
had a parameter added to it and was made package 
private.&lt;P&gt;&lt;P&gt;

I would suggest adding the following code to 
AbstractResultSetTable:

&lt;PRE&gt;
public static ITableMetaData createTableMetaData
\(String name, ResultSet resultSet, IDatabaseConnection 
connection\) throws SQLException, DataSetException \{
DatabaseConfig config = connection.getConfig\(\);
IDataTypeFactory dataTypeFactory = 
\(IDataTypeFactory\)config.getProperty\(

DatabaseConfig.PROPERTY\_DATATYPE\_FACTORY\);
return createTableMetaData\(name, resultSet, 
dataTypeFactory\);
\}
&lt;/PRE&gt;
&lt;P&gt;
so that metadata can be directly created using the 
result set.&lt;P&gt;
Ideally, perhaps, AbstractResultSetTable, and its 
subclasses, as well as the factories, would have a 
constructor and method which simply took a table name, 
a result set and the database connection. Currently you 
have that when you supply the SQL, but in my case the 
resultset is generated as part of a multi-result set 
stored proceedure, or via some other code which is 
itself under test, so all I have is the result set, and I 
can't send the raw SQL.

