tickets.description:
The column names in the ORDER BY clause are not quoted.  This causes problems if a column name is a reserved word for a database.

The defect is in org.dbunit.database.DatabaseDataSet in the getSelectStatement method.  The correct code is:


// order by
for \(int i = 0; i &lt; primaryKeys.length; i++\)
\{
if \(i == 0\)
\{
sqlBuffer.append\(" order by "\);
\}
else
\{
sqlBuffer.append\(", "\);
\}
// BUG FIX HERE:
sqlBuffer.append\(DataSetUtils.getQualifiedName\(null,
							   primaryKeys\[i\].getColumnName\(\), 
escapePattern\)\);
\}

This affect results when using schema qualified table names \(e.g. useQualifiedTableNames="true" with the Ant task\).  The result is that the names are escaped as "schema.table" instead of "schema"."table".  The resulting names are meaningless \(at least for the SQL92 compliant database I am using\).

I am not sure what the exact bug is, but I have fixed it by changing 
public static String getQualifiedName\(String prefix, String name, String escapePattern\)
in org.dbunit.dataset.DataSetUtils.  Some of the values getting passed around are not what I would expect from their names \(prefix and name already combined into one value\), so the bug may lie elsewhere.  However, changing that would be a rather large change and this fix is focused and easy.

The corrected code is:

public static String getQualifiedName\(String prefix, String name,
String escapePattern\)
\{
if \(escapePattern \!= null\)
\{
// BUG FIX HERE
	    if \(name.indexOf\("."\) &gt;= 0\)
	    \{
		prefix = name.substring\(0, name.indexOf\("."\)\);
name = name.substring\(name.indexOf\("."\) + 1\);
\}
// BUG FIX ENDS

prefix = getEscapedName\(prefix, escapePattern\);
name = getEscapedName\(name, escapePattern\);
\}

