I am quite sure that the string concate must take longer because of the internal creation of a StringBuffer and some other stuff going on there.

And here is a little proof for that \(really very simple\) showing that string concat takes about 2 times longer than Integer.toString\(\):


public static void main\(String\[\] args\)
\{
long firstStart = System.currentTimeMillis\(\);
for\(int i=0; i&lt;60000; i++\)
\{
Integer.toString\(i\);
\}
long firstEnd = System.currentTimeMillis\(\);
// String concatenate
String s;
for\(int i=0; i&lt;60000; i++\)
\{
s = "blabla " + i;
\}
long secondEnd = System.currentTimeMillis\(\);
System.out.println\("Integer.toString: " + \(firstEnd-firstStart\) + ", String concat: " + \(secondEnd-firstEnd\) \);
\}


So the best in our case is to avoid any operations by prechecking the "isXxxLevelEnabled\(\)".

