tickets.description:
IEEE binary floating-point values are possible in Oracle.  BINARY\_DOUBLE in particular is the only decent solution to underflow exceptions that the Oracle JDBC driver will toss at you if you try to bind something like 1E-200 to a numeric column.

The changes to the Oracle10 data type factory are minimal:

if \("BINARY\_DOUBLE".equals\(sqlTypeName\)\) \{
return DataType.DOUBLE;
\}
if \("BINARY\_FLOAT".equals\(sqlTypeName\)\) \{
return DataType.FLOAT;
\}

Note that to exercise this, you need to configure a connection pool/data source such that it will provide the Oracle JDBC driver with the necessary property to turn on support for IEEE conversion.  Here is a Spring example with C3P0:

&lt;bean id="dataSource" class="com.mchange.v2.c3p0.ComboPooledDataSource"&gt;
&lt;\!-- must set driver properties first, before C3P0 uses the other setters and they add their values --&gt;
&lt;property name="properties"&gt;
&lt;\!-- Oracle-specific property to support IEEE floating-point --&gt;
&lt;value&gt;SetFloatAndDoubleUseBinary=true&lt;/value&gt;
&lt;/property&gt;
&lt;property name="driverClass" value="$\{jdbc.driverClass\}"/&gt;
&lt;property name="jdbcUrl" value="$\{jdbc.url\}"/&gt;
&lt;property name="user" value="$\{jdbc.username\}"/&gt;
&lt;property name="password" value="$\{jdbc.password\}"/&gt;
&lt;/bean&gt;

Related to \#2545095 there are more locations where the catalogName/schemaName must be interchangable.

