I found a workaround for my main problem, which is the constraint violation during the DELETE statements while cleaning the DB. I just disable the constraints on all tables before the setUp\(\) method is called, then I enable them afterwards. Here is the code:

In the constructor of the test class \(or some superclass for all tests\):

Statement stmt = jdbcConnection.createStatement\(\);
for \(String tableName : getTablesFromFile\(\)\) \{
String sql = "ALTER TABLE " + tableName + " NOCHECK CONSTRAINT all";
stmt.executeUpdate\(sql\);
\}

\-----------
getTablesFromFile\(\) returns an String\[\] of table names.

And I overwrite the setUp\(\) method:

@Override
protected void setUp\(\) throws Exception
\{
super.setUp\(\);

// enable constraints in db.
// they have been disabled in the constructor to avoid errors while DBUnit deletes current data.
// DBUnit will delete the data in the setUp\(\) method. This constructor is executed before that.
try
\{
Statement stmt = jdbcConnection.createStatement\(\);
for \(String tableName : getTablesFromFile\(\)\) \{
String sql = "ALTER TABLE " + tableName + " WITH CHECK CHECK CONSTRAINT all";
stmt.executeUpdate\(sql\);
\}
\} catch \(Exception e\)
\{
e.printStackTrace\(\);
System.exit\(1\);
\}
\}

This solution might be database specific \(I use MS SQL Server 2008\), but it removes the problem, that you need to have an ordered dataset to insert into the db. However, I am still interested in the solution for the bug report I posted, since I would like to use DBUnit with other DB systems in the future.

